// Javascript string search Methods
//String indexOf();[used to find the first occurrence of a specificed value withnin or an array and returns its index.if the value is not found it return -1]

 <!DOCTYPE html>
 <html>
 <body>
 <h1>Hello everyone</h1>
 <p>i am wrinting indexOf() method</p>
 <p id="name"></p>
 <script>
 let text = "Locate the text where it occur";
 let index=text.indexOf()("where");// it give the place number where the 'where' exit in this where came in 16 place so that's the output
 document.getElementbyId("name").innerHTML=index;
 </script>
 </body>
 </html>

// lastIndexOf() Method[retern the index of last occurence of a specified text in a string]
 <!DOCTYPE html>
 <html>
 <body>
 <h1>Hello everyone</h1>
 <p>i am wrinting indexOf() method</p>
 <p id="name"></p>
 <script>
 let text = "Locate the text where it occur where";
 let index=textlastIndexOf()("where");// it give the place number where the 'where' exit in this where came in  31 place(last where string) so that's the output
 document.getElementbyId("name").innerHTML=index;
 </script>
 </body>
 </html>

 //search() method[searches a string for the strings and returns the position of the match]
  <!DOCTYPE html>
 <html>
 <body>
 <h1>Hello everyone</h1>
 <p>i am wrinting indexOf() method</p>
 <p id="name"></p>
 <script>
 let text = "Locate the text where it occur";
 let index=text.search()("where");// in this search() method serath the where string it come in the 16th place so it give the output 16
 document.getElementbyId("name").innerHTML=index;
 </script>
 </body>
 </html>

 /*The two methods, indexOf() and search(), are equal?

They accept the same arguments (parameters), and return the same value?

The two methods are NOT equal. These are the differences:

The search() method cannot take a second start position argument.
The indexOf() method cannot take powerful search values (regular expressions).*/

// match() method[returns an array containing the results of matching a string against a string 

